1) Introduction

In this lab you will practice writing simple functions, and some basic examples to make sure that the functions work as expected. Later in the course we will see how to write assertions (i.e. tests) for your functions in a more formal way.

In addition to writing the functions, you should also practice documenting your functions. Writing this type of documentation should become second nature. To do this, include roxygen comments such as:

  • #' @title Name of your function
  • #' @description What the function does
  • #' @param x input(s) of your function
  • #' @return output of your function

2) Polynomials

In this problem we want to see whether the graph of a given polynomial will cross or touch the x axis in a given interval.

Let’s begin with the polynomial:

\[ f(x) = x^2 - 1 \]

The first thing to do is to write a function for the polynomial, for instance:

poly1 <- function(x) {
  x^2 - 1
}

Once you have a function for the polynomial, you can create a set of pairs of points \(x\) and \(y = f(x)\), and then use them to graph the polynomial

# set of points
x <- seq(-4, 4, length.out = 50)
y <- poly1(x)

# graph polynomial
plot(x, y, type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = "#FB7215", las = 1)
abline(h = 0, v = 0, col = '#888888aa', lwd = 1.5)
title(main = expression(paste(f(x), ' = ', x^2, (x - 1))))

2.1) Your Turn: Polynomial functions

Write functions and graph the following polynomials in the x-axis interval -4 to 4:

  1. \(f(x) = x^3\)
# your code
poly2 <- function(x){
  x^3
}

x <- seq(-4, 4, length.out = 50)
y <- poly2(x)

plot(x, y, type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = "#FB7215", las = 1)
abline(h = 0, v = 0, col = '#888888aa', lwd = 1.5)
title(main = expression(paste(f(x), ' = ', x^3)))

  1. \(f(x) = (x^2 - 1)(x + 3)^3\)
# your code
poly3 <- function(x){
  (x^2 - 1) * (x + 3)^3
}

x <- seq(-4, 4, length.out = 50)
y <- poly3(x)

plot(x, y, type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = "#FB7215", las = 1)
abline(h = 0, v = 0, col = '#888888aa', lwd = 1.5)
title(main = expression(paste(f(x), ' = ', (x^2 - 1), (x + 3)^3)))

  1. \(f(x) = (x^2 - 1)(x^2 - 9)\)
# your code
poly4 <- function(x){
  (x^2 -1) * (x^2 - 9)
}

x <- seq(-4, 4, length.out = 50)
y <- poly3(x)

plot(x, y, type = 'l', lwd = 3, col = "#FB7215", las = 1)
abline(h = 0, v = 0, col = '#888888aa', lwd = 1.5)
title(main = expression(paste(f(x), ' = ', (x^2 - 1), (x^2 - 9))))

3) Area of a circle

Consider a circle with radius = 2. The area of this circle can be computed in R as:

# area of circle with radius 2
r <- 2
area <- pi * r^2
area
## [1] 12.56637

3.1) Your Turn: circle_area() version 1

Write a function circle_area() that calculates the area of a circle. This function must take one argument radius. Give radius a default value of 1. Don’t forget to include roxygen comments to document your function!

# your code
circle_area <- function(radius = 1){
  area <- pi * radius
  return (area)
}

Test your function with:

  • circle_area()

  • circle_area(radius = 3)

# your tests
circle_area()
## [1] 3.141593
circle_area(radius = 3)
## [1] 9.424778

3.2) Your Turn: circle_area() version 2

Modify your circle_area() function in order to include a stop() statement. If radius is negative, then the function should stop with a message like: "radius cannot be negative".

# your code
circle_area <- function(radius = 1){
  if (radius < 0){
     stop("radius cannot be negative")
  }
  area <- pi * radius
  return (area)
}

Test your modified circle_area() with radius = -2; the function should return a stop message:

# your test
circle_area(radius =  -2)
## Error in circle_area(radius = -2): radius cannot be negative

4) Area of a Cylinder

For a given cylinder of radius \(r\) and height \(h\) the surface area \(A\) is given by:

\[ \text{area} = 2 \pi r h + 2 \pi r^2 \]

For example. Say you have a cylinder with radius = 2, and height = 3.

# cylinder variables
r = 2  # radius
h = 3  # height

# area of cylinder
2 * pi * r * h + 2 * pi * r^2
## [1] 62.83185

Notice that the formula of the area of a cylinder includes the area of a circle: \(\pi r^2\).

4.1) Your Turn: cylinder_area() function

Write a function cylinder_area(), that calls circle_area(), to compute the area of a cylinder.

# area of cylinder
cylinder_area <- function(radius = 1, height = 1){
  if (radius < 0){
    stop("radius cannot be negative")
  }
  if (height < 0){
    stop("height cannot be negative")
  }
  area <- 2 * pi * radius * height + 2 * pi * r^2
  return(area)
}

This function must take two arguments: radius and height. Give both arguments a default value of 1. In addition, the function should stop if any of radius or height are negative.

Test your function with:

  • cylinder_area()

  • cylinder_area(radius = 2, height = 3)

  • cylinder_area(radius = -2, height = 1)

  • cylinder_area(radius = 2, height = -1)

  • cylinder_area(radius = -2, height = -1)

# your tests
cylinder_area()
## [1] 31.41593
cylinder_area(radius = 2, height = 3)
## [1] 62.83185
cylinder_area(radius = -2, height = 1)
## Error in cylinder_area(radius = -2, height = 1): radius cannot be negative
cylinder_area(radius = 2, height = -1)
## Error in cylinder_area(radius = 2, height = -1): height cannot be negative
cylinder_area(radius = -2, height = -1)
## Error in cylinder_area(radius = -2, height = -1): radius cannot be negative

5) Even and Odd Numbers

Any number that can be exactly divided by 2 is called as an even number. R provides the modulo operator, "%%" that can be used to determine if a number is even or odd.

To be more precise, the modulo operator returns the remainder or signed remainder of a division.

For example, 4 %% 2 evaluates to 0, because 4 divided by 2 has a quotient of 2 and a remainder of 0:

# 4 is exactly divisible by 2
4 %% 2
## [1] 0

In contrast, 5 %% 2 would evaluate to 1, because 5 divided by 2 has a quotient of 2 and a remainder of 1

# 5 is not exactly divisible by 2
5 %% 2
## [1] 1

5.1) Your Turn: Even number

Write a function is_even() that determines whether a number is even (i.e. multiple of 2). If the input number is even, the output should be TRUE. If the input number is odd, the output should be FALSE. If the input is not a number, the output should be NA

# your code
is_even <- function(x){
  if (is.numeric(x)){
    return (x %% 2 == 0)
  }
  return(NA)
}

Test your function with:

  • is_even(10)

  • is_even(33)

  • is_even('a')

# your tests
is_even(10)
## [1] TRUE
is_even(33)
## [1] FALSE
is_even('a')
## [1] NA

5.2) Your Turn: Odd number

Use your function is_even() to write a function is_odd() that determines if a number is odd (i.e. not a multiple of 2). If a number is odd, the output should be TRUE; if a number is even the output should be FALSE; if the input is not a number the output should be NA

# your code
is_odd <- function(x){
  !is_even(x)
}

Test is_odd() with the following cases:

  • is_odd(1)

  • is_odd(4)

  • is_odd('a')

# your tests
is_odd(1)
## [1] TRUE
is_odd(4)
## [1] FALSE
is_odd('a')
## [1] NA

6) If Conditionals

Say you have a number \(x\), and you want to compute another number \(y\) that takes a value depending on \(x\) as follows:

\[ y = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if} & x < 0 \\ & \\ x & \text{if} & x \in [0, 100] \\ & \\ 100 & \text{if} & x > 100 \end{cases} \]

6.1) Your Turn: squish() function

Write a function squish() that “squishes” a number into the interval \([0, 100]\), so that a number less than 0 is replaced by 0 and a number greater than 100 is replaced by 100.

# your code
squish <- function(x){
  if (x < 0){
    x = 0
    return(x)
  }
  if(x >= 0 & x <= 100){
    return(x)
  }
  x = 100
  return(x)
}

Test squish() with:

  • squish(-5)

  • squish(180)

  • squish(50)

  • squish(0)

  • squish(100)

squish(-5)
## [1] 0
squish(180)
## [1] 100
squish(50)
## [1] 50
squish(0)
## [1] 0
squish(100)
## [1] 100
